statement_latex:
Let

\begin{align*}
a = \begin{bmatrix}
-3 \\ -3 \\ 3
\end{bmatrix}
\qquad 
b = \begin{bmatrix}
2 \\ -3 \\ -2
\end{bmatrix}
\qquad 
c = \begin{bmatrix}
3 \\ -4 \\ 12
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

Further, let $d = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ k \\ 2k+1 \end{bmatrix}$ where
\emph{k} is a parameter. Find the value of \emph{k} for which \emph{a}
and \emph{d} are orthogonal.

statement_raw:
Let

:&lt;math>
a = \begin{bmatrix}
-3 \\ -3 \\ 3
\end{bmatrix}
\qquad 
b = \begin{bmatrix}
2 \\ -3 \\ -2
\end{bmatrix}
\qquad 
c = \begin{bmatrix}
3 \\ -4 \\ 12
\end{bmatrix}
&lt;/math>

Further, let &lt;math> d = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ k \\ 2k+1 \end{bmatrix}&lt;/math> where ''k'' is a parameter.  Find the value of ''k'' for which ''a'' and ''d'' are orthogonal.
